# Screen Layout Patterns

Every screen in this app follows one of these structural skeletons. Pick the right one **before** writing any JSX.

## Pattern A — Header Background with Content Overlap

Used when an image/gradient header sits behind a nav bar AND content (avatar, card) that visually overlaps the background boundary.

**Key insight**: The background is absolutely positioned with a fixed height. Content flows in normal document order on top of it. You control how far content "overlaps" the background by adjusting the padding on the content section — NOT by changing the background height.

```tsx
<View style={{ position: "relative" }}>
  {/* Background — fixed height, absolutely positioned behind everything */}
  <View style={{ position: "absolute", top: 0, left: 0, right: 0, height: BG_HEIGHT, overflow: "hidden" }}>
    <ImageBackground source={bgImage} resizeMode="cover" style={{ width: "100%", height: "100%" }} />
  </View>

  {/* Nav bar — sits at the top, on top of the background */}
  <View style={{ paddingTop: Math.max(insets.top, 44) }}>
    <NavigationBar ... />
  </View>

  {/* Overlap content — paddingTop controls how far into the background it sits */}
  <View className="items-center px-xl" style={{ paddingTop: OVERLAP_PT }}>
    {/* Avatar, card, or hero content here */}
  </View>
</View>
```

**How to calculate OVERLAP_PT**: Look at the design spec. The avatar/content top edge should land at a specific Y relative to the background. Subtract the nav bar height (status bar + nav = ~100px) from that Y to get the padding.

Examples: `goals_details` (bg 172px), `profile_settings` (bg 173px)

## Pattern B — Header with Negative-Margin Body Overlap

Used when the header is a self-contained block (with rounded corners, padding, etc.) and the body section overlaps upward into it.

```tsx
{/* Header — paddingBottom creates the overlap zone */}
<View style={{ borderBottomLeftRadius: 24, borderBottomRightRadius: 24, overflow: "hidden", paddingBottom: OVERLAP }}>
  <Image source={bg} style={{ position: "absolute", width: "110%", height: "120%", top: 0, left: 0 }} resizeMode="cover" />
  <View style={{ height: Math.max(insets.top, 44) }} />
  {/* Header content */}
</View>

{/* Body — negative marginTop pulls it up into the header's paddingBottom zone */}
<View style={{ marginTop: -OVERLAP }}>
  {/* Body content */}
</View>
```

**Critical**: `paddingBottom` on header and `marginTop` (negative) on body MUST use the same `OVERLAP` value.

Example: `home` screen (OVERLAP = 128)

## Pattern C — Flat Screen (No Overlap)

Used for screens with a plain or gradient background, no image, no overlap.

```tsx
<View className="flex-1" style={backgroundStyle}>
  <View style={{ height: Math.max(insets.top, 44) }} />
  <NavigationBar ... />
  {/* Optional: TabBar, filters, etc. */}
  <ScrollView className="flex-1" contentContainerStyle={{ paddingBottom: 120 }}>
    {/* Content */}
  </ScrollView>
</View>
```

Examples: `analytics_overview`, `analytics_breakdown`, `transaction_history`

## Sticky Bottom Bar (All Screens)

Always absolutely positioned at the bottom, outside the ScrollView. Content needs `paddingBottom: 120` to avoid occlusion.

```tsx
<View style={{ position: "absolute", bottom: 0, left: 0, right: 0, paddingBottom: insets.bottom }}>
  <BottomNavBar activeTab="..." />
  <HomeIndicatorBar type="default" />
</View>
```

## Decision Checklist

1. Does the design have a background image/gradient behind the header? → **A or B**
2. Does the body content overlap upward into the header (negative margin)? → **B**
3. Does content sit on top of the background via padding? → **A**
4. No background image, flat layout? → **C**
